Some media outlets are reporting it as a ransomware attack, but according to a note reportedly sent to city employees and shared on Twitter, the hackers didn't encrypt data. The group reportedly demanded a payment of four bitcoins by 5pm today, Monday 28 October, or they will release the compromised data. UPDATE: Please find the media release about COJ hacked computer systems. COJSystemBreach Update: City continues to work towards restoring service. City of Joburg is HACKED. Time is running out... https://t. City Power spokespeople told reporters that the attackers "Won't get a cent". In July, a ransomware infection encrypted City Power's database, internal network, web apps, and website, making it difficult for people to purchase power from the company.